When blood is oxygenated by the placenta, it passes through umbilical veins into the ductus venosus. The ductus venous shunts blood away from the liver, only allowing enough blood to provide nutrients and oxygen . This promotes liver development

Blood also enters the right atrium from the rest of the foetus‚Äôs body, but this blood is deoxygenated. The deoxygenated blood is sent down to the right ventricle, which will eject this blood through the pulmonary artery
